--></description></item><item><title>Text-Based Object Discovery</title><link>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/project/text-based-object-discovery/</link><pubDate>Tue, 15 Nov 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/project/text-based-object-discovery/</guid><description/></item><item><title>The Three Musketeers in a Semicircle Problem</title><link>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/post/the-three-musketeers-in-a-semicircle-problem/</link><pubDate>Sat, 29 Oct 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/post/the-three-musketeers-in-a-semicircle-problem/</guid><description>&lt;p>I came across this interesting problem on which my seniors were brainstorming late at night. It requires a bit knowledge of continuous random variables in probability and little bit visualization capability.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The problem goes like this… &lt;br>
&lt;strong>There are three musketeers who stand on a circle randomly, which follows Uniform(0, 2πr) independently where r is the radius of the circle. They can help each other if they are close enough in case of a sudden attack by the enemies. Find the probability of them lying on the same semicircle.&lt;/strong>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Read my detailed solution at: &lt;a href="https://medium.com/@rishidarkdevil/the-three-musketeers-in-a-semicircle-538677acc067" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Three Musketeers in a Semicircle Problem&lt;/a>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>The Rabbit and the Stone Problem</title><link>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/post/the-rabbit-and-stone-problem/</link><pubDate>Thu, 27 Oct 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/post/the-rabbit-and-stone-problem/</guid><description>&lt;p>I have this friend of mine, who constantly pokes me to solve interesting puzzles. He sometimes even rings me up, just to look at the problem he sent :P This is one of those problems, that I enjoyed working on. It requires understanding of basic probability theory, counting and some time to stick to a problem that interests you.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The problem goes like this… &lt;br>
&lt;strong>There are 7 stones in a row labelled 1 to 7 from left to right. A rabbit starts at stone 1 and on each turn hops to a new stone that they haven’t visited yet. After visiting all the stones, what is the probability the rabbit made exactly one leftwards jump?&lt;/strong>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Read my detailed solution at: &lt;a href="https://medium.com/@rishidarkdevil/the-rabbit-and-the-stone-problem-90ff6c1d54e0" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Rabbit And The Stone Problem&lt;/a>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>The Classic Urn Color Change Problem</title><link>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/post/the-classic-urn-color-change-problem/</link><pubDate>Sat, 22 Oct 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/post/the-classic-urn-color-change-problem/</guid><description>&lt;p>Anyone who has taken probability class in their college or school is familiar with probability problems involving the classic urn (basically a bag) setup which contains balls of different colors and the professor asks you to find the probability of occurrence of some stupid pattern. This is one of those problems.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The problem goes like this… &lt;br>
&lt;strong>You are given an urn with 100 balls (50 black and 50 white). You pick balls from urn one by one without replacements until all the balls are out. A black followed by a white or a white followed by a black is “a color change”. Calculate the expected number of color changes if the balls are being picked randomly from the urn.&lt;/strong>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Read my detailed solution at: &lt;a href="https://medium.com/@rishidarkdevil/classic-urn-color-change-problem-c82a24aa549" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Classic Urn Color Change Problem&lt;/a>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>The Chessboard High Five Problem</title><link>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/post/the-chessboard-high-five-problem/</link><pubDate>Fri, 21 Oct 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/post/the-chessboard-high-five-problem/</guid><description>&lt;p>Just another day, when I was browsing through my Instagram feed, my friend sent me this interesting yet not so difficult problem involving understanding of basic probability, counting and bit of time to pause the temptation to scroll the rest of your Instagram feed.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>So, the problem went like this..&lt;br>
&lt;strong>Imagine you have a regular 8 x 8 chessboard, with 64 people standing on each of the 64 squares. At the same time every person turns to face one of their neighbors with equal chances i.e. say the person near the center of the chessboard can face any direction with 1/4 probability, a person at the top of the chessboard (but not the corners) has probability 1/3 to face any of its neighbors, similarly all others. Now, if two people are facing each other they give each other a high five. Find the expected number of high fives.&lt;/strong>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Read my detailed solution at: &lt;a href="https://medium.com/@rishidarkdevil/the-chessboard-high-five-problem-fafcae9acfdb" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Chessboard High Five Problem&lt;/a>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Visuo-Textual Joint Embedding</title><link>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/project/visuo-textual-joint-embedding/</link><pubDate>Mon, 15 Aug 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/project/visuo-textual-joint-embedding/</guid><description/></item><item><title>Scanned Document Classification</title><link>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/project/scanned-document-classification/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Aug 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/project/scanned-document-classification/</guid><description/></item><item><title>Advanced Summer School on NLP 2022</title><link>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/talk/advanced-summer-school-on-nlp-2022/</link><pubDate>Mon, 20 Jun 2022 13:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://RishiDarkDevil.github.io/rishi-portfolio/talk/advanced-summer-school-on-nlp-2022/</guid><description>&lt;!--
